Define sum and mean functions to handle NAs appropriately

#Define function to correctly sum across duplicates (sum(NA,NA,NA) = NA, while sum(1,NA,NA) = 1, which is not the default for na.rm parameter)

my_sum <- function(x){
  if(all(is.na(x))){
    return(as.numeric(NA))
  }
  else{
    return(sum(x, na.rm = TRUE))
  }
}

#Define function to correctly sum across duplicates (sum(NA,NA,NA) = NA, while sum(1,NA,NA) = 1, which is not the default for na.rm parameter)

my_mean <- function(x){
  if(all(is.na(x))){
    return(as.numeric(NA))
  }
  else{
    return(mean(x, na.rm = TRUE))
  }
}

#make depth numeric
FishGlob_clean.singleseason[,depth := as.numeric(depth)]

#make survey and survey unit factors
FishGlob_clean.singleseason[,survey:=factor(survey)][,survey_unit:=factor(survey_unit)]

#adjust years
FishGlob_clean.singleseason[,year_adj := year-min(year)+1]

#add column for yearly summed # of hauls
FishGlob_clean.singleseason[,haul_id_count_annual := uniqueN(haul_id),.(year, survey_unit)]

#add column for yearly summed # of spp
FishGlob_clean.singleseason[,spp_count_annual := uniqueN(accepted_name),.(year, survey_unit)]

#add column for avg depth per year
FishGlob_clean.singleseason[,depth_annual_avg := my_mean(depth),.(year, survey_unit)]

#add column for depth range per year
FishGlob_clean.singleseason[, depth_annual_range := 
  if (all(is.na(depth))) {
    NA_real_
  } else {
    max(depth, na.rm = TRUE) - min(depth, na.rm = TRUE)
  }, 
  by = .(year, survey_unit)
]

#add column for avg latitude per year
FishGlob_clean.singleseason[,latitude_annual_avg := my_mean(as.numeric(latitude)),.(year, survey_unit)]

#add column for latitude range per year
FishGlob_clean.singleseason[,latitude_annual_range := max(latitude, na.rm =T)-min(latitude, na.rm =T),.(year, survey_unit)]


#for some reason this step is causing issues turning a numeric column into logical, so we're going to manually implement this by merging DT...ugh

#function for season
# Function to classify dates into seasons for Northern Hemisphere
get_season_northern <- function(date) {
  y <- year(date)
  winter_start <- as.Date(paste0(y-1, "-12-21"))
  spring_start <- as.Date(paste0(y, "-03-21"))
  summer_start <- as.Date(paste0(y, "-06-21"))
  autumn_start <- as.Date(paste0(y, "-09-21"))
  autumn_end <- as.Date(paste0(y, "-12-20"))
  
  if (date >= winter_start & date < spring_start) {
    return("Winter")
  } else if (date >= spring_start & date < summer_start) {
    return("Spring")
  } else if (date >= summer_start & date < autumn_start) {
    return("Summer")
  } else if (date >= autumn_start & date < autumn_end) {
    return("Fall")
  } else {
    return("Winter")
  }
}

# Function to classify dates into seasons for southern Hemisphere
get_season_southern <- function(date) {
  y <- year(date)
  winter_start <- as.Date(paste0(y-1, "-12-21"))
  spring_start <- as.Date(paste0(y, "-03-21"))
  summer_start <- as.Date(paste0(y, "-06-21"))
  autumn_start <- as.Date(paste0(y, "-09-21"))
  autumn_end <- as.Date(paste0(y, "-12-20"))
  
  if (date >= winter_start & date < spring_start) {
    return("Summer")
  } else if (date >= spring_start & date < summer_start) {
    return("Fall")
  } else if (date >= summer_start & date < autumn_start) {
    return("Winter")
  } else if (date >= autumn_start & date < autumn_end) {
    return("Spring")
  } else {
    return("Summer")
  }
}
  

#get season
dates_regions[, season := mapply(function(date, survey_unit) {
  if (survey_unit %in% so_hemis) {
    get_season_southern(date)
  } else {
    get_season_northern(date)
  }
}, date, survey_unit)]

Proportion test (prop homogenizing/differentiating vs.Â prop not)

H0: The null hypothesis is that the two hemispheres from which the regions were drawn have the same true proportion of homogenizers. A: The alternative is that this proportion is different in at least one of the hemispheres.

H0: The null hypothesis is that the two hemispheres from which the regions were drawn have the same true proportion of differentiators. A: The alternative is that this proportion is different in at least one of the hemispheres.

For Jaccard: Differentiation was more common in the southern hemisphere (four out of eight surveys), while homogenization was more common in the northern hemisphere (eight out of 29 surveys). START HERE
